<h2>Event in January 2019</h2>
<br><br>
<h3> Extreme snowfall in the Alpine region </h3>
<br><br>
The alpine region encountered several episodes of extreme snowfall in the first half of January, especially on the northern side. This resulted in blocked roads, stranded tourists and the highest levels of warnings for avalanches. The western part of Austria, southern part of Germany and eastern part of Switzerland encountered one of the ten wettest January's since the beginning of the measurements (source: ZAMG, MeteoSwiss, DWD). Figure 1 shows the amount of precipitation compared to the average precipitation of 1981-2010 in Austria. In some places precipitation was more than three times the normal value. Many records of snowfall were broken as well. In Hochfilzen (962 m) 450 cm of fresh snow was measured in 15 days. Between 12 and 14 January Switzerland regionally encountered 90 up to 140 cm of fresh snow (see Figure 2).
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jan2019/Figure1.png"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2019/Figure1.png" width="400px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Precipitation in January 2019 in Austria in comparison with the average precipitation amount 1981-2010. 100% is the average. Source: ZAMG.</em>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jan2019/Figure2.png"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2019/Figure2.png" width="500px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: Precipitation amount from 12-14 January in mm in Switzerland. Source: MeteoSwiss. </em>
<br><br>
The high amounts of snowfall were caused by what is in German called a "Nordstaulage". Between a high pressure system above western Europe and a low pressure system above (north)eastern Europe a northerly wind developed over the Alps (see Figure 3). The northerly wind transported cold and sometimes humid air towards the mountains. When this air was forced to go up at the northern side of the mountains the air cooled down and precipitation was formed. Due to the cold temperatures most precipitation fell as snow.
At the southern side of the Alps, where the air descended, it was drier and milder than normal in January.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jan2019/Figure3a.PNG"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2019/Figure3a.PNG" width="250px"></a>
<a href="../images/jan2019/Figure3b.PNG"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2019/Figure3b.PNG" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 3: Weather map of January 5 (left) and January 13 (right). Source: KNMI.</em>
<br><br>
